<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Male genitalia</emphasis>
: Median lobe strongly acuminate at apex (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11</figureCitation>
) and in lateral view with the apex curved inwards (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">12</figureCitation>
), internal sac with two fascicles of small spines (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11</figureCitation>
) and apical structure formed by modified spines of squamiform shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Female</emphasis>
: General appearance similar to male (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–2" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 2. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Habitus in dorsal view 1 male 2 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures1-2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673887" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2</figureCitation>
), but with posterior margin of the elytra with the fringe of tomentose setae broadest and more developed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), tergite IV clearly longer (0.55 mm), practically as long as length of elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), sternite III longer, without tuft of erect setae and rugulose at the base (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparative notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is well distinguished from the rest of the known species of the genus by its marked troglomorphism, such as the reduction of the eyes (only three unpigmented ommatidia) and an extraordinary general elongation of the body (especially of the head) and appendages (antennae, maxillary palps and legs). It is also characterised by the small size of the tomentose foveae on the head, which are large in the rest of the known species, the elytra have a complete dorsal carina (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3–7" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3 - 7. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. head 3 dorsal view 4 lateral view. Head appendages 5 A antennae 5 B maxilar palpi. Elytra and abdomen in dorsal view 6 male 7 female." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures3-7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673888" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
), which is absent or slightly elevated in the rest of the known species of the genus, and the aedeagus is quite different (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 8–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 8 - 12. Geopselaphus bullonorum Hernando &amp; Castro, sp. nov. Ventral part 8 male 9 female. Aedeagus 10 - 11 dorsal vision 12 lateral vision." figureDoi="10.3897/subtbiol.43.83592.figures8-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673889" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10-12</figureCitation>
). It has also been compared with its geographical neighbour 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Besuchet" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus longulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longulus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus longulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Besuchet, 1961, an endogean species showing some elongation of the head and palps, but always in comparison with the other endogean species and without any comparison with the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Based on the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hernando &amp; Castro" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus bullonorum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullonorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus bullonorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Coquerel" baseAuthorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geopselaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Geopselaphus sencieri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sencieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geopselaphus sencieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Coquerel, 1858), distributed in Algeria, Morocco and the extreme south of the Iberian Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation author="Jeannel, R" journalOrPublisher=") (Serie A: Zoologie)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 233" refId="B11" refString="Jeannel, R, 1956. Les Pselaphides de l'Afrique du Nord. Essai de biogeographie berbere. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris (N. S.) (Serie A: Zoologie) 14: 1 - 233" title="Les Pselaphides de l'Afrique du Nord. Essai de biogeographie berbere. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris (N. S." volume="14" year="1956">Jeannel 1956</bibRefCitation>
), both species have an acuminate median lobe, and the internal sac is very similar, consisting of two fascicles of spines (see Besuchet 1961).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Geographic distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">So far, only known from the typical locality.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The Cueva de la Pileta has a total length of 2.406 m and a maximum slope of 102 m. All the specimens were captured wandering on walls in the sector called &quot;La Gran Sima&quot;, which is in one of the deepest parts of the cave, approximately 400 m from the cave entrance. This cave harbours a rich community of terrestrial subterranean arthropods, 32 species have been recorded so far (
<bibRefCitation author="Perez, T" journalOrPublisher="Gota a gota" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="58 - 64" refId="B19" refString="Perez, T, Meseguer, A, Bullon, JT, 2013. Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana). Gota a gota 3: 58 - 64" title="Aproximacion al estudio de los invertebrados de la Cueva de la Pileta (Benaojan, Malaga, Espana)." volume="3" year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
